A quick idea for a simple dynamo powered windmill. UNTESTED.  
Using 2 SP dynamo hubs with built in sealed bearing, some 9mm rod, some wood and your 3D printer, we can make a VAWT or water wheel to power a lighting system and recharge system, for 12v battery and USB.   
we can mount the fan body to the disk brake mount on the dynamo hub x2, push the rod through and lock it down with the dual locknuts, the bearing in the hubs take the load, the 9mm rod stays still and the fan moves the outside of the hubs around on the bearings. we use one hub and fan on bottom and one hub and fan on top, put in as many middle fans you need to get the power needed to turn the hubs. you could use the spacer.stl to add extra support with extra bearings if needed if you make a big stack of them. still need to add bearing retainer into spacer.stl if I do that.  
Have easy circuits for ya to boost up to 10w output from each dynamo, so 20w max limit for this unit. have easy lighting circuits and charger systems that a monkey could build...but first we test the genny.  
its still just a idea...not sure of how much power the fans can take from a given wind speed, or how high I will need to stack it to get the power I want. or if I made my fans too small and have too many of them...gota start some where to tweek I guess.  
Made to print on my soon to turn up UP printer, it is 130mm round / 100mm high, not sure if it will warp, UNTESTED.  
So I think just build a water wheel that I hope to use for wind...guess I will find out if it works soon when my printer gets here, please test and report if built!   
Cheers ktronik

title: Lab-on-an-Arduino Spectral Absorbance Shield aka Optical Density Meter

description.text: This Arduino Shield allows to measure the optical density (OD) aka turbidity through a standardized cuvette. 3-Channels for different wavelengths, using 5mm LEDs. The design fits nicely a TIL-99 phototransistor. see details on: http://hackteria.org/?p=2194

The shield was made using 3mm MDF and laser cut. The settings for rastering need to be optimized to have the right thickness to perfectly fit the LED in between. Same for the depth of the pin-header row.
To be able to raster from both sides, 2 sequential steps are needed. After the first 2 layers are rastered deeply and everything is cut out, flip over the main shield part to finalize the other side.

comments.text:
Keep in mind that absorbance is not nephelometric tubidity, which is what is used for the determination of water quality.
Turbidity is a measure of the amount of suspended solids in a liquid. But transmittance of light is hindered by not only suspended solids, but by the absorption characteristics of dissolved matter (color for example). So measuring absorbance/transmittance may or may not correspond to actual turbidity. The way to overcome this problem is to measure scattered light instead of transmitted light: Shine LED and measure at a 90 degree angle. Electronic nephelometers use scattered light measurements for turbidity determination.

After using a coffee dispenser for a while, I enjoyed the convenience, but always had to rap on the box to jolt the coffee down into the measuring thing. It needed better flow into the measuring cup.
Also the capacity was a bit low. I designed and printed an upper box extension. But that didn't cure the flow problems. So, I redesigned it. This Version 2 has mostly vertical walls and a capacity of about 55 tablespoons, for a dozen or so 12-cup pots.
Coffee still cannot be positively relied upon to fill the cup every time so I give it a knuckle rap, or jiggle the cup, just to make sure. There's no option to mount this new one directly to a surface. Due to the different shape, the wall mounting bracket from the earlier version is required. That bracket file is included here. The plan is to permanently attached the upper part to the lower with ABS cement. The assembly is about 8 inches tall and 4 inches across. (Printed using Afinia defaults. Medium speed and fill, with rafts, but with thick 0.40mm layers to save time.) Upper cylinder: 79grams, 135 minutes
Lid + cup will fit on the Afinia platform: 76 grams, 105 minutes
Wall bracket: 40g, 60 min. Main body: 100 minutes, 67 grams if it's oriented as shown, which was most economical for my printer and settings. There's no real good orientation. I had to sand the cup opening a little bit due to layer imperfections. The cup from the first version will work in this one too. The lid was printed as shown in hopes of a smooth exposed top surface, but that didn't pan out... Rather than presenting an attractive curve, the slight hump only enhances horizontal layering. Files are SAE / Imperial. If metric print software imports Lilliputian parts, scale up by a factor of 25.4

description.text: Unleash your creativity on your iPhone by putting your own 3D design on the back your case! This case allows you to do that without the need for supports. Check out my Han Solo iPhone 6 Case to see how this would look. Update: I added a .3 mm tolerance as well.

Design Process
  • Find out what tolerance you need for your inside piece (this might take some trial and error, but the .5mm tolerance should work well for the first test).
  • Download the inner piece and upload it into your preferred 3D modeling software. Also, insert the 3D object that you want on the back of your case.
  • Use a boolean to make the bottom of your 3D object flat and then stick it on to the top of the inner piece. Make sure that the object is not hanging over the side of the inner piece (changing the orientation and resizing can help fix this).
  • Export the file as an stl.
    • Printing
  • Print your customized inside piece.
  • Print your preferred outside piece style.
    • Assembly
  • Put the two pieces together with the 3D object going through the back of the outside piece.
  • Put your phone in and swag on in peace!

description.text:
Hello fellow Thingiversers! Up for your consideration is this printable and functional earth anchor. Nothing to tie your winch line to? No problem! Use it to pull your rig out of a tight jam on flat ground or in the rocks and trees. Go ahead, get stuck. This bad boy is the only winching accessory your scale rig can't get by without. (get it? get by?) Throw out your hooks, tie it right to the winch line and never get stuck again!!
Ridiculously simple, extremely effective

Settings are:
Printing this with an Infill of 100% is probably best.
1 or 2 shells
.2 layer or better.
No raft or support is needed (raft is optional)
You could scale it up a bit to fit the look of the truck. The larger the better.
Use ABS preferably. I haven't tried PLA and I am sure it will still work but I think that ABS will hold up better to the riggers of being used and abused. It offers better deflection and tensile strength in this application.
I have included both components on one tray and separately if you want a bi-coloured print or paint as you like. I used Tamiya chrome silver model paint (X11) with a light coat of fine white primer. Not a scratch on it yet.
The parts just slide together. You could glue or acetone the parts together or leave them separate. The design of the anchor in use will hold it in place and if you need to swap parts you could.

description.text: I got the idea for this from the Reverse Engineer's Ring. To quote that thing's description: Sans professional rite of passage, the Reverse Engineer's Ring is a variation of a Canadian engineering tradition - the Iron Ring. The Reverse Engineer's Ring is to serve as a reminder that you don't have to be building bridges or parking structures to have the potential to accidentally ruin somebody's day or somebody's life with your creations. Out of respect for the original tradition, the design of the ring is coarser in appearance (six facets top and bottom instead of twelve). The ring should be worn on the little finger of your dominant hand, such that when you draw or write, the flat edges rub against the page. I used the wonderful Nut Job with the measurements I wanted, lobotomized the thread cutting bit of code, and simplified/edited it in Blender to finalize it. description.text: My motor side has always been wonky as someone printed the parts for me but it didn't have enough infill, was in ABS, and the 8mm holes were just too large so I created this to go along with my Prusa I3 Rework X-Idler Drop In Replacement ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:699285 ) and man has it made a difference. No more wobbly now all I have is the 8mm smooth rod flex which all 8mm smooth rods will flex (I wish I had known this a little over a year ago). I built this to be more solid and to place the Z axis m5 nut in a more appropriate place (lower down towards the middle instead of the top like the original) with a deeper well so the m5 has less chance of popping out.
I printed mine with .12mm layer height, .26mm first layer 40% rectilinear infill in PLA with support.  All holes were perfect with my PLA but your setup may be different.

title: ZMR250 camera mount without top deck

description.text:
Update 10.07.2015:
Added ~15° version.
Added slightly taller version to accomodate cameras with their plugs along the bottom edge.
Added STL files, even though they're fairly messy.

Update 08.06.2015:
Added a "sturdy" version. The previous version will protect the camera better by breaking on impact, but I felt it broke a bit too quickly sometimes. This one is strengthened and should be able to handle lighter impacts better.

I use my ZMR 250 without the top deck, as it weighs almost 20 unneccesary grams and I have my battery below the quad rather than up top. I needed a simple, removable camera mount, and after seeing the (source) mount recently, I modified it to this (also adjusted slot width and depth, added gap to hide cable tie in at the bottom).
  • Fits onto the two front post/landing gear screws
  • Cable tie mount (2.5x200mm), easy to replace
  • Camera is not held so firmly that it will be damaged in a crash, will pop out to the back
    • Print with low infill, no support, I used 15 or 20%. M3 lock nuts will fit on it.

description.text: This is version 2 of the Dustcover for the Mantis-30 router (thing:6115). As this router normally uses a dremel/rotary tool it is quite loud and can produce quite a lot of dust. This cover keeps both inside the box.

The dxf or 3dm file is laid out with different layers. The names of the layers hold the instructions how to cut it out. description.text: SUPER COOL MINI ROBOT HAND! This is a miniature robotic hand made by Open Bionics while exploring the idea of making fully functional items in a single print. You push the base of the hand to make it open and when you release it springs shut. It makes a fantastic business card holder and is also great at grabbing onto things and picking things up. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-n3yM-Suhuk&feature=youtu.be It prints in a single piece out of NinjaFlex (knuckles down). At Open Bionics we're working hard on making affordable robotic hands. Follow us at @openbionics for more cool stuff. Check out our website www.openbionics.com to see more of our work.

We print using Lulzbot 3D printers (a TAZ 2, a TAZ 4 and an A0-101). The Cura profile we use is included in the source files. These need to be printed really slowly as they have very tall islands with small printbed contact area.   
From our experience you need to keep the travel slow - around 60mm/s and the print speed around 10mm/s to get these little guys to print! Layer height seems to work best at 0.2mm.
